  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This preprint, subsequently published in a leading journal, investigates the role of cilia maintenance in cerebellar granule cell neurogenesis, with significant implications for our understanding of cellular biology.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research presented in the preprint titled \"Programmed withdrawal of cilia maintenance followed by centriole capping leads to permanent cilia loss during cerebellar granule cell neurogenesis\" has garnered attention in the academic community, accumulating 15 citations as of now. This suggests that the work is contributing meaningfully to ongoing discussions in cellular biology. The formal publication has further solidified this impact, yielding an additional 10 citations, showcasing the relevance of the research post-peer review.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Key institutions backing this work, such as the Janelia Research Campus, Howard Hughes Medical Institute, and The University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center, lend considerable credibility to the findings. The collaboration among these esteemed organizations highlights the interdisciplinary nature of the research, reflecting the importance of integrating diverse expertise in advancing scientific knowledge.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Notably, the research demonstrates a commitment to open science practices, as evidenced by its early sharing on bioRxiv. By making the findings accessible prior to formal publication, the authors engaged the scientific community early, facilitating immediate discourse and promoting collaborative efforts. This practice is essential for fostering transparency and enhancing the pace of scientific advancement.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, the proven downstream reuse of materials from this research, demonstrated by an active count of 17, underscores the work's technical value and relevance to ongoing studies in the field. Such reuse is indicative of the contribution this study makes towards establishing foundational knowledge, enabling further exploration and validation of cellular mechanisms involved in neurogenesis.</p>",
